2500|$|It is {{possible}} for railroad employees to get a [...] "coordinated" [...] retirement and disability benefits. The U.S. Railroad Retirement Board (or [...] "RRB") is an independent agency {{in the executive branch}} of the United States government created in 1935 to administer a social insurance program providing retirement benefits to the country's railroad workers. Railroad retirement Tier I payroll taxes are coordinated with social security taxes so that employees and employers pay Tier I taxes {{at the same rate as}} social security taxes and have the same benefits. In addition, both workers and employers pay Tier II taxes (about 6.2% in 2005), which are used to finance railroad retirement and disability benefit payments that are over and above social security levels. Tier 2 benefits are a supplemental retirement and disability <b>benefit</b> <b>system</b> that pays 0.875% times years of service times average highest five years of employment salary, in addition to Social Security benefits.|$|E
