5000|$|China is also {{experiencing}} {{a gap between}} housing price and affordability as it moves away from an in-kind welfare <b>benefit</b> <b>system</b> to a market-oriented allocation system (Hui et al. 2007). Most urban housing prior to 1978 in the planned-economy era consisted of nearly free dwellings produced and allocated by the unsustainable single-channel state-funded system. The goal of China's housing reform started in 1978 was to gradually transform housing from a [...] "free good" [...] to a [...] "subsidized good" [...] and eventually to a [...] "commodity", the price of which reflects true production costs and a market profit margin. In 1998 China accelerated its urban housing reform further moving away from an in-kind welfare <b>benefit</b> <b>system</b> to a market-oriented allocation system, with the state reducing its role in housing provision. The reform is followed by increasing home ownership, housing consumption, real estate investment, as well as skyrocketing housing price.|$|E
